    "summary": "Hattusa, located near modern Bogazkoy in north-central Turkey, served as the capital of the [[event:54|Hittite Empire]] from around 1600 BC until its destruction at the end of the Bronze Age around 1178 BC. The city occupied a naturally defensible ridge surrounded by deep ravines and was enclosed by massive stone walls stretching approximately eight kilometers in circumference, punctuated by monumental gates decorated with sculptural reliefs including the famous lion and sphinx gates.\n\nAt its height, Hattusa covered an area of approximately 180 hectares and housed royal palaces, temples (over thirty have been identified), administrative buildings, and vast storage magazines. The city's archives, preserved in thousands of clay cuneiform tablets, constitute one of the most important written sources for the ancient Near East, containing royal annals, treaties, religious texts, mythological narratives, and the oldest surviving Indo-European literature. Hattusa was destroyed and abandoned around 1180 BC, apparently by invaders possibly connected to the [[event:1815|Bronze Age Collapse]]. The site was rediscovered and identified in the nineteenth century and has been excavated continuously since 1906.",
